  "notes": "Early New Persian / Classical Persian (Dari) (~900‚Äď1200 CE). First attested ~900 CE in eastern Khorasan/Transoxiana. Literary corpus: Shahnameh (Ferdowsi ~1000), Divan of Hafez, Rumi. KEY INNOVATIONS vs. Middle Persian: (1) Arabic script adopted (with additional letters Ŕĺ ŕÜ ŕė ŕĮ for Persian); (2) Massive Arabic loanwords ‚ÄĒ Arabic consonants őł, √į, ńß,  ē, q     appear in spelling but assimilated phonologically to s, z, h,  Ē, …£; (3) Classical 6-vowel system: ńĀ, ńď/eňź, ńę, Ňć/oňź, Ňę, a; (4) /v/ stabilised; /r/ ‚Üí […ĺ] (tap) in most positions. This Classical system is the reference for Dari (fa-AF) and Tajik (tg).",
